metadata.name: Resonance #226
metadata.description:
An exploration of movement, textures, chaos, order, water and fire. Discovering the breaking point in balanced shapes. Is it from nature or out of space? Resonance is a study of previously used techniques combined with Perlin noise

Press s in live mode for a download

Download a higher resolution by adding to the URL:
&density=2 / &density=3 / &density=4

Lammetje December 2022

metadata.name: ExoVille #139
metadata.description:
At the time of minting of "ExoVille" we broke mercury thermometer in our apartment.
I don’t know what can that tell about ecology, living on our own or other planets, but close neighborhood, packed apartments, favelas or cities are for sure always exciting :)

Thank You


press ‘2’ for 2x, ‘4’ for 4x or ‘8’ for 8x image resolution png
press ‘s’ to save canvas.

Created with love for p5js and generative art

@Qotonana
August, 2022.

metadata.name: Let Me Paint #16
metadata.description:
“Let Me Paint” is a computer’s request to create a painting, abstract expressionism in this case, which machines can’t do, since they cannot have feelings.
On the other hand, this is my own request to myself. The request to do what you want, without thinking much about whether it will bring any benefit (in any sense) to me or others.
In an effort to do anything with some profit in the future, I have driven myself into these thoughts. And even now I “draw” using a computer, hiding it behind a wall of code to make it look reasonable (to me).

——————

To change the size of the image, open it in live view and add ‘&size=[size (6400 max.)]’ to the end of the URL.
To render a version without grain add ‘&grain=false’ to the end of the URL.

Controls:
[S] — save the image.

Created with p5.js and GLSL.
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

——————

hrunz. — Jan. 2023.

metadata.name: System β #60
metadata.description:
α -> β is about "Increases in magnitude and decreases in computation". And still related the fleeting time in the generating process.

My role in this work is more of a discoverer than a creator. 

Try to reveal the possibilities of time perception in the generative art through negotiating with incomprehensible mathematical equations.

What I want to explore through this work is that behind the generated results, the dynamic process of generations are equally diverse and unpredictable.

When we watch the generating process displayed on the computer, changing instantly, moving, multiplying, disappearing, and we hesitate, wonder, pause, await, as if many possibilities of time perception have emerged in the fragmented moments.

_
press [1] -> β 
press [2] -> β⁰　 
press [3] -> β¹
-
Press [s] in live view to save as PNG.
Press [d] in live view to save as hi-res PNG.
-
If you need your collection in SVG format, feel free to DM me.

metadata.name: Reverie #117
metadata.description:
Reverie: a state of being pleasantly lost in one's thoughts; a daydream.

I love impressionist paintings of nature, where the visible brushstrokes give a glimpse into the artist’s process. With this collection I aimed to capture a slice of nature with distinctly digital “brushstrokes”. Looking closely, you can see many of the lines, curves and polygons that combined to form each Reverie. 

Keyboard Interactions:
[z] Change color / season. There are two seasons, winter and not-winter. Weather (wind, ice) is as unpredictable as it is in nature.
[p] Play / pause. Automatically cycle through colors and seasons.
[s] Save 1000x1000px image (instant)
[2] Save 2000x2000px image (fast)
[4] Save 4000x4000px image (slowish)


Elsif 2022, made with p5js.

metadata.name: Urbanscape - Genuary Edition #28
metadata.description:
As the last day of January and the beginning of the fxhash festival, with regard to the theme of genuary 31 and inspired by my last work and making changes to it, I decided to present a more complex version of urban structures with many changes in it, So the structure of urban blocks, lights and atmospheres and other important things have been changed. Therefore, this work is a recreated and remixed version of my earlier work with some major changes to achieve a more complex structure and arrangement.
_________________________

To see the artwork in high quality, open it in live view and add “&res=1 to 25” to the URL.

Made with p5js.

#genuary32nd

metadata.name: Dualidad #81
metadata.description:
The concept of 'Dualidad' (duality) is brought to life through the use of opposing elements, circles, and rectangles, in the artwork. 

The circles, like the stillness of a calm pond, remain in close places while they continuously transform. In contrast, the rectangles are a representation of movement and change, constantly traveling across the canvas. 

This balance of opposing elements creates a dynamic tension that draws the viewer in, leaving them mesmerized by the ever-evolving artwork. Expect to see a range of emotions, from the euphoria of joy to the depth of sorrow, as you explore the duality of this project.

-----

The generative process of each artwork has a typical completion time ranging from 20 seconds to 2 minutes, depending on your PC.

-----

Tested on Brave, Opera and Mozilla (Linux systems). Brave and Safari (macOS)


-----

Press "e" to save a high res png while in live mode.

-----

Artwork by @cristianrohr (2023)

Made with P5js and <3

metadata.name: Kinetograms #418
metadata.description:
Each Kinetogram traces the movement of a number of simple shapes constrained within a single cell or a grid of cells. Forces are applied to the shapes in the form of attraction, gravity or shaking.

Some Kinetograms are partially or completely reflected, vertically or horizontally, some with chromatic replacement.

The aspect ratio is 3:4. The palettes are predominantly based on found textile patterns.

Press 's' to save a png image. Press 'e' to redraw and export a 4K png image. Note that drawing and physical simulation takes some time.

For interactive use, press 't' to tilt the board and 'c' to clear the board.

Written in p5.js with 2D physical simulation using Matter.js. Developed in and optimized for Chrome.

metadata.name: In Between #21
metadata.description:
In Between

Genuary is an artificially generated month of time where we build code that makes beautiful things, with 31 prompts to base your code art off. Genuary 2023 took place during the month of January 2023. Afterwards, as it happens, comes Genuary 32nd. This is an imaginary week, during which we develop one of our Genuary pieces into a 32 edition "not very long"-form generative project on fx(hash).

My Genuary 32nd project is based on Genuary 22nd: Shadows, the design of which again was based on the "art deco" pattern from day 20.

The patterns form a grid-like fence structure, dividing the space and creating an infinite cage. Light coming from the outside casts stark shadows on the floor. Several variations on halftoning techniques are used to portray tone, occasionally destroying depth perception into an abstract interplay of form.

The code of this piece has been diminished into a mere 3397 characters.

You can use the URL-parameter &m=2 as a resolution multiplier, to render images larger than your screen.

(c) 2023 by Piter Pasma. https://piterpasma.nl

metadata.name: Unfinished Loom #69
metadata.description:
The 'Unfinished Loom' is a generative system that produces variations of itself through rotations, displacements, and self-repetition. 

Self-similarity in the loom is achieved by repeating the double grid system and its elements vertically (using the 'o' and 'l' keys) and horizontally (using the 'i' and 'k' keys).

Pressing 'a' produces automatic changes, while pressing 'x' reverts to the original composition.

By clicking on the canvas, you can play with colors and transparency. 

The '1' key toggles between disorder and order. 
The '2' and '3' keys allow you to toggle displacements.
The '4' key enables you to switch between entropy or not.
The '5' key lets you switch between mixed textures or assigned textures. 

You can reduce, amplify, or flip the displacement using the 'u' or 'j' key. 
To remove a color press 'c'. To reset to all colors, press 'v'.

You can save a PNG file using 's', a JPG using 'd', a PNG with twice your window height using 'f', and a print size image using 'g'.

This work explores composition based on generative double grid system, where rotations, displacements and noisy lines intertwine to form a playful loom.

Created with p5.js rendering in WEBGL.

metadata.name: Espacios comunes #252
metadata.description:
At moment we decide to draw a square on top of a circle, we are defining a time arrow, a third dimension on the 2D plane, where shapes can be on o top of each other, come one after the other. In this project i wanted to remove that time arrow, that third dimension, and leave the 2D plane as flat as possible.

Shapes are not drawn in sequence, they are formed by the continuous addition of points to each region defined by the shapes intersections. Not a single region is on top of the other. They are the result of the combination of shapes, and defined by them. Horizontal, decentralized societies. Espacios comunes. We can see the circles, squares, plane cuts, but we cannot give them an order or authority.

-----

Key controls:

- UP arrow: Increases the sketch resolution. It will take longer to render but it will produce better quality images.
- DOWN arrow: Decreases the sketch resolution.
- f: Removes or adds an empty frame around the image.
- d: Increases the points density. More points will be painted and regions will become more full.
- n: Increases the pixel noise.
- b: Decreases the pixel noise.
- z: Switches on and off the simple pixel sorting algorithm. Move the mouse left and right to change the pixel stickiness.
- x: Switches on and off a more complex version of the pixel sorting algorithm.
- i: Displays some log information.
- p: Pauses the sketch.
- s: Saves a screenshot of the artwork. The image resolution will depend on the sketch resolution, which is controlled by the UP and DOWN arrows.

-----

URL controls:

width=2000 will set the sketch width to 2000 pixels.
proportion=2.3 will set the sketch width-to-height ratio to 2.3.
You can combine these two parameters to create any image output you want. For example, to create an image that is 3000 pixels wide and 5000 pixels high, one just needs to add &width=3000&proportion=0.6 to the URL.

-----

Special thanks to @andregorayeb (Gora) and @ItonkStudio (Itonk) for letting me use some of their color palettes for this project.

-----

License: CC BY 4.0

This project makes use of the p5.js library. Thank you to all the people that contributed to it.
https://p5js.org

metadata.name: Crash Euphoria #174
metadata.description:
My first foray into shaders and GLSL: This piece experiments with layering many textures guided by an underlying pattern. Each pixel value dictates which pattern is displayed. There are varying levels of imperfections in each pattern, some choose a single color, some use a color guide pattern, some individual strokes decide on another color altogether. These layers are compiled in a shader and warped.

Press 's' in live view to save a png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Ailerons #80
metadata.description:
Ailerons, littering the factory floor, custom made and ready to be fitted to their respective aircraft. An accent trickles across the canvas, coloring any object in its path.

A study of light, built entirely in a 2d renderer, creating light and shadow with math and logic.

Press 's' to save a .png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Décollage #274
metadata.description:
A generative sketch based on the concept of décollage, an artistic process that involves cutting or tearing pieces of an original image. The resulting outputs bear a resemblance to artworks produced using the lacerated poster technique, where posters are layered and torn to reveal parts of the posters underneath.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels. Note that this will not work with sizes beyond 5000 pixels.

(Allowlist is based on quantity of previous works owned).
